                rend="underline">years, perhaps for ages</hi>, a <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">mound</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">Hill</add> of<lb/>
considerable height has been formed, from<lb/>
the centre of which the Geyzer issues.<lb/>
- |_ It rises through a perpendicular and<lb/>
cylindrical pipe, or <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">shaft, seventy</hi> feet in<lb/>
depth, and eight feet and a half in diameter<lb/>
which opens into a bason or <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">funel</del> funnel,<lb/>
measuring fifty-nine feet from one edge <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">of it</add> to<lb/>
the other. - The bason is circular, &amp;<lb/>
the sides of it, as well <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of</del> those of the<lb/>
pipe, are polished quite smooth by the<lb/>
continual friction of the water. &amp; They<lb/>
are both formed with such <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">mathematical</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">truth</hi>, as to appear constructed by art.<lb/>
- The declivity of the <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">mound</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">Hill</add> begins<lb/>
immediately from the borders of the bason.<lb/>
- The incrustations are in some places<lb/>
worn smooth, by the overflowing of the<lb/>
water; in most however the<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">y</add> rise in<lb/>
numberless little tufts, which bear a<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="42"
                xml:id="pb-42"
                facs="#i42"/>
            <lb/>
40<lb/>
resemblance to the heads of cauliflowers.<lb/>
except that they are <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">rather</add> more prominent. &amp;<lb/>
are covered, by the falling of the finer<lb/>
particles of spray, with a chrystaline<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">effloresence</hi> so delicate as scarcely to bear<lb/>
the slightest <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">touch</del>. touch. - <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Unmolested</hi>.<lb/>
the effloresence gradually hardens, and<lb/>
although it looses its first delicacy, it<lb/>
still <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">remains exceedingly</hi> beautiful.<lb/>
These incrustations are of a light brown<lb/>
colour, and extended a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">great way</hi>, in various<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">directions</hi>, <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">from the borders of</hi> the bason.<lb/>
To the northward, they reach to a distance of<lb/>
82 feet; to the East of 86 to the south of 118;<lb/>
and of 124 to the west. - They are very hard<lb/>
and do not appear in any part decaying,<lb/>
or <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">mouldering</hi> into soil.<lb/>
When our guides first led us <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">to</add> the<lb/>
geyzer, the bason was filled to within a<lb/>
few feet of its edge. "the water <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">a</del> was<lb/>
transparent as chrystal, a slight steam<lb/>
only arose from it, and the surface was<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="43"
                xml:id="pb-43"
                facs="#i43"/>
            <lb/>
41<lb/>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">ruffled</add> but by a few bubbles, which now and then<lb/>
came from the bottom of the pipe. - We<lb/>
waited with anxiety for several minutes<lb/>
expecting <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">for several minutes</del> at every<lb/>
instant some interruption to this tranquility<lb/>
- |_ on a sudden, another spring immediately<lb/>
in front of the place, on which we were<lb/>
standing, darted its water above an hundred<lb/>
feet into the air with the velocity of<lb/>
an arrow, and the jets succeeding this<lb/>
first eruption were still higher. This<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">was</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">is</add> the spring <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">already mentioned under</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">the name of</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">called</add> the new Geyzer.<lb/>
|_ While gazing in silence and wonder<lb/>
at this unexpected and beautiful display,<lb/>
we were alarmed by a sudden shock of the<lb/>
ground under our feet, accompanied with<lb/>
a hollow noise not unlike the distant <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">firing</hi>
            <lb/>
of Cannon. - Another shock soon followed<lb/>
and we observed the water in the<lb/>
bason much agitated. - |_ The Icelanders<lb/>
hastily laid hold of us, and forced us to<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="44"
                xml:id="pb-44"
                facs="#i44"/>
            <lb/>
retreat some yards. - The water in the<lb/>
mean time boiled violently, and heaved as<lb/>
 if some expansive <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">power</add> were labouring beneath<lb/>
its weight, and some of it was thrown<lb/>
up a few feet above the bason. -<lb/>
again there were two or three shocks<lb/>
of the ground and a repetition of the<lb/>
same noise. - In an instant the<lb/>
surrounding Atmosphere was filled with<lb/>
volumes of steam rolling <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">over</hi> each<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">other</hi> as they ascended, in a manner<lb/>
inexpressibly beautiful, and through<lb/>
which, columns of water, shivering into<lb/>
foam, darted in rapid <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">succission</hi> to<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">heights,</hi> which (at the time,) we were<lb/>
little qualified to estimate. - |_ Indeed<lb/>
the novelty and splendour of such a<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">scene</del> scene had affected our imaginations<lb/>
so forcibly, that we believed the extreme<lb/>
height of the jet to be much greater<lb/>
than it was afterwards determined to<lb/>
be, |_ in a subsequent eruption <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag115"
                ref="#person_950"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag115" type="person">
          M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Baine
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
ascertained by means of a Quadrant the<lb/>
greatest elevation to which the jets of water were<lb/>
thrown to be 96 feet<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="45"
                xml:id="pb-45"
                facs="#i45"/>
            <lb/>
43<lb/>
Much of the water began to descend<lb/>
again at different heights, and was again<lb/>
projected by other columns, which meet<lb/>
it, as they arose. At last having filled<lb/>
the bason it rolled in great waves over<lb/>
its edge, and forming numberless rills,<lb/>
made its way down the side of the mound<lb/>
|_ Much was lost in vapour also, and still<lb/>
more fell to the ground, in heavy<lb/>
showers of spray. - |_ The intervals<lb/>
at which the several jets succeeded<lb/>
each other were too short for the eye<lb/>
to distinguish them. - As they rose<lb/>
out of the bason, the<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">y</add> reflected by their<lb/>
density the purest and most brilliant blue.<lb/>
In certain shades, the colour was green<lb/>
like that of the sea; but in their<lb/>
further ascent all distinction of colour<lb/>
was lost and the jets broken into a<lb/>
thousand parts, appeared white as snow<lb/>
|_ Several of them were forced upwards<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="46"
                xml:id="pb-46"
                facs="#i46"/>
            <lb/>
perpendicularly; |_ but many, receiving a slight<lb/>
inclination, as they burst from the bason<lb/>
were projected in beautiful curves, and<lb/>
the spray which fell from them, caught<lb/>
by a succeeding jet was hurried away<lb/>
still higher than it had been <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">perhaps</del>
            <lb/>
before. *<lb/>
The jets were made with<lb/>
inconceivable velocity and those which<lb/>
escaped uninterupted, terminated in <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">shape</del>
            <lb/>
sharp points and lost themselves in<lb/>
the air - |_ The eruption changing its<lb/>
form at every instant and blending<lb/>
variously with the clouds of steam that<lb/>
surrounded <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">it</del> it, continued for ten or twelve<lb/>
minutes; the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">water</hi> then subsided through<lb/>
the pipe and disappeared<lb/>
|_ The eruptions of the geyzer<lb/>
succeeded each other with some degree<lb/>
of regularity, but they are not equally<lb/>
violent, or of equal duration. - <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Some</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">lasted scarcely</del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="47"
                xml:id="pb-47"
                facs="#i47"/>
            <lb/>
45<lb/>
Some lasted scarcely eight or ten, while<lb/>
others continued with unabated violence<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">fifteen or eighteen</hi> minutes, |_ between the<lb/>
great eruptions while the pipe and<lb/>
bason were filling, the water burst<lb/>
several times into the air to a<lb/>
considerable height. - These partial<lb/>
jets however, seldom exceeded, a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">minute</hi>
            <lb/>
and sometimes <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">not only</add>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">not</del> a few <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">seconds</hi> in<lb/>
duration<lb/>
After the eruption of it had been<lb/>
violent, the water sank into subterranean<lb/>
caverns, and left the pipe quite empty.<lb/>
If the eruption had been moderate, the<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">subsidence</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">falling</add> of the water was proportionally<lb/>
less - |_ The first time the pipe was<lb/>
perfectly emptied, we sounded its depth<lb/>
and found the bottom very rough<lb/>
and irregular. The pipe remains but<lb/>
a very short time empty. After a<lb/>
few seconds the water <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">rushes into it</hi>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
